The first virtual provider is already coming to Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services as they are offered by their partners in West Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces classics at lower prices.
Perhaps he will not wait for a long time.
That the Czech mobile providers are working among the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This was confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČTÚ, which warned that the price for a SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission on roaming fees regulation, it is likely to come to a paradox situation - for some of the Czech mobile providers' customers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices so high in Czech Republic compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of the competition that really makes a fighting answer.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, but in Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators are happy to shake that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (Czech Telecommunications Authority) (Czech Telecommunications Authority) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past often stated that there is no room for another supplier in Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (also, he would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another way – a virtual provider.
Precisely the entry of virtual providers to the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile providers had to respond.
Prior to the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were voices similar to the Czech market in the UK.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don’t need to look for examples for a long time.
In February we reported this about the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the five-largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns in Czech Republic, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target audience.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need a lot fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone talks and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good chess train to put on a non-clinic target audience.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose mobileking – the provider they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
Tough to say whether a similar concept might be able to catch foot as in Poland as well in Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický’s press spokesman also doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, he is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In Czech Republic, the mobile providers
However, it is almost sure that when a virtual mobile operator conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in Czech Republic, the negotiations are not very hopeful.
It will rather come to a market entry of mobilking in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studničková, speaker of the Finance Group Penta, in a telephone call for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that current mobile operators in Czech Republic are not particularly appropriate to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
Your interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has long been showing the GTS Novera Group, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business customers field.
“We have a great interest in providing our customers not only fixed networks but also mobile communications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated with all Czech mobile operators about this possibility.
With some of them we were already able to achieve negotiation progress," said the press spokesman of the group Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times come now.
Not official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far, this is surrounded by an inconceivable wall of silence.
“At this moment, we don’t assume that there is place in Czech Republic for a fully valid virtual provider.
The Czech market has large specifications compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area,” said Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2’s press department in its explanation for Mobil.cz.
Other suppliers also indicate the specification of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokesman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the statement of O2: "Until we have found no viable and both-sided advantageous project on which we could continue to build."
And she adds: “In the T-Mobile network, a virtual provider will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a specific offer to be able to think so shortly.”
Vodafone rather focuses on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: “For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of division of costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we view from customers’ perspective as the best.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a quick mobile Internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The action of the mobile provider is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would lead to a decline in prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be easier to enter the market?
The fact that the vendors can draw on a string when it comes to something, also demonstrates the long way around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ went at the moment when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also demonstrates publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is right as an argument why a virtual provider should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competition in the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new actor on the market itself and above all its services would make high requirements.”
Given this approach, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprised by the mobile operators.
It is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition, unlike the UK and other highly developed states.
It only owns the Bureau for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
But this concerned all of this problem with his very typical attitude.
“The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract between a mobile provider and a virtual provider has come to rent the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded until now, because the offering of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers,” said Chalupa in his answer to our inquiry from the ÚOHS Foreign Relations Department.
Such a formulation would not be surprised by representatives of the suppliers.
An authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, should make sure that no one abuses its position on the market is more than threatenable.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa added: “Abroad, where virtual providers work normally, it is observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services.”
Probably, however, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, really shocking is the almost touching balance of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is just a coincidence is on the hand.
Just like the absolutely equal gasoline price at the gasoline stations is certainly only accidental and the result of a hard competition fight.
“The authority has not discovered any signs in this matter that indicate an action against the competition, and therefore it has no reason to interfere with the matter in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions on the market.
The necessary tools for the opening of the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be missing from the telecommunication regulatory authority,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by ČTÚ, according to telecommunications, is a single market from the perspective of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the entry into the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile provider has – logically – the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you don’t take this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are incredibly similar.
Complaints of a number of stakeholders (including the above-mentioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they face very similar obstacles during negotiations with all providers.
The abolition of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances from the whole matter.
This was observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted novel of the Telecommunications Act has not been able to enforce the expansion of ČTÚ's competences in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of professionals had promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS only have to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's going on when no one looks
Notwithstanding, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers remains equal to several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies who spend their own prize lists for mobile telecommunications services but are only partly public.
Usually, they are companies that operate in multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services provide Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach to elected.
The joke of the thing is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similarly-typed reselling.
“If there are cases that you describe, it may be a breach of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society,” Martina Kemrová answered on our question.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing is not about the responsible of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such action.
Indeed, from the activities of these companies, they are not overlooking profits, while, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický is aware of possible problems: “The law allows such speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone doesn’t run on their name, so they can’t have it fully like the normal customers of the mobile provider.”
But that alone, at least, would have to be strange.
Furthermore, there is another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile providers close their eyes before such action, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competencies to discover such activities, and if it does not want, it does not have to be satisfied with the statement of the providers, they knew nothing and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the entry into the market of virtual providers has brought a significant decline in prices in the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a too small, or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, just in these moments, the regulatory bodies that did not attempt to preserve the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator emerged, and followed another.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing the entire case like a hot potato.
Based on our experiences, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclearness in the skills in these cases is more than favourable.
But let's not throw the flints into the grain.
If the background information is right and soon a virtual provider appears, the Czech mobile market may soon move again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to refusing further interested parties (to discriminate).
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive than the rest of Europe.
