Debate about two-lingual education: education in English-speaking environment
In this edition of the "Education Watch" Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for two-lingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Scientific Officer in Caliphonic Studies and Senior Director in Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-writer of the book "Not as well as thinking: Why the middle class needs a school selection."
To address the Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama’s suggestions on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's election campaign mentioned that "the probability of Afro-American and Hispanic students to successfully complete school is lower than white students" - which is true.
In order to close this distance of performance, Obama’s educational plan especially recommends a two-lingual transitional phase in training for those who first learn English.
Nevertheless, the question to Obama is whether his engagement in two-language education, which focuses on teaching in other languages than English, is opposed to his interest in reducing the distance in school services.
Let’s take an example of “Sixth Street Prep”, a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom are only recently in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of the fourth class students passed the state examination in math at a good level.
Surprisingly, 93% of children from the fourth school year were also evaluated as well in the English exam.
This amazing success has been achieved with other methods than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on review and exercise, on steady control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach to which the education is running in an English-speaking environment. That’s exactly the point that Obama should take into account, says the school director Linda Mikels.
This approach places emphasis on the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialty lessons.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejected the idea of two-lingual education, told me that the school would have a remarkable success with a student who had come from Mexico shortly before it. 12 months later, you would enter the classroom and no longer recognize it.
“It works,” she noted, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English students?
The school’s achievements would make the answer to this question easier, but the educational political positions within its own party (the national non-image groups have long supported the idea of two-lingual education) and its own consistent support for two-lingual education make predictions about Obama’s response uncertain.
While he agrees to the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the topic by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation targeting "only English".
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can Spanish."
If Obama actually wants to close the distance of performance, he should carefully consider educational models that work instead of despising and trivializing them.
