Discussion - From Blood that Became Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of her founding yesterday, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, was very happy because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most safe and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, she has regained the public's confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the donation service of the Canadian Red Cross during the 1980s were contaminated with HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada in February 1994 initiated a public investigation conducted by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light into the circumstances that led to such tragedy, and developing guidelines to prevent a renewed disaster of this kind.
While Judges Krever still hesitated to submit his report, several provinces at the time set a committee on the legs, whose aim was to develop a new system for managing blood conservations in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this job.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were founded in Canada: Hema-Quebec, responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the huge efforts to improve the safety of blood conservations and through work in this field during the following years, we have gained the public’s confidence, she says, before proudly emphasizing that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec’s population had trust in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, retains awareness that ‘confidence is something extremely fragile’.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec acts on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the appearance of numerous cases of human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, this woman tells, who has been heading since the foundation of 1998.
And we had no mind if this disease could be transferred over the blood.
So we called on one of the main guidelines of Krever and Gélineau's reports, which says that you can apply exclusion measures if you don't know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as it is obviously the case in the Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proven that this disease is transferred over the blood.
Thus this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has a very meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique of detecting HIV appeared on the market: Nucleic Acid Tests (NSTs), which allowed to demonstrate the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case in the tests previously used.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood through our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk of certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and you could not recognize it was significantly reduced.
These improvements allowed significantly to reduce the risk of transferring AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, it means you should distribute 12 million blood conserves before someone was infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec spreads between 400,000 and 500,000 blood conservations every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case in which HIV was transferred through a blood conservation occurs.
“I think you can feel comfortable today when you get or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore your health,” said Hema-Quebec director.
“Our challenge for the next 10 years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can enter the system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, just like the Westnil virus, is transmitted through insects over blood.
We have to continuously monitor," Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply along with a safe supply.
“The need increases because the population ages.
Because treatments to combat cancer are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, among which on average only 3% of Quebec’s suitable inhabitants are donated to blood.
Any healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the appropriation criteria can give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who provide their blood are not accepted because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, for example, and whoever travelled to a country where malaria is spread is excluded from blood donation for a year.
With these 3% we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of stocks are very rare.
But you need to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
"Life is so hectic today that you rarely find the time to spend an hour in donating blood," Francine Décary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec provides not only blood preserves, but human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye apples and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are investigated, processed and frozen before being interstocked at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public blood bank of Quebec’s umbrella cord.
In the navel cord, previously considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousand umbrella cord blood samples, and we plan to remove more than thousand annually.
“We should probably begin early next year with making it available for transplants,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbrella-line blood decrease as very popular.
“Many mothers are convinced of not having access to this, because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec’s hospitals.
