The psychology of overbiding - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the feil proposed.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic basics of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people don't want to beat themselves in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lotto while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were studied using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to earn money, however, an increased activity of striatum, a complex below the brain ridge, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent’s overbidding plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to encourage their thesis, the research group economists have also employed investigations to track money.
In this case, three groups should participate against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, then they made their stakes.
Any other group was also promised $15 reward, in case they emerge as a winner from the game.
The third group received $15 prior to the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis at one was on winning, while at the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypotheses expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group playing “contra losing” were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or the “winning” group.
“These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
Indeed, the behaviors observed in auctions have so far only been based on the joy of gaining or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was dissolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we have now parallel a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor at the University of New York’s Economic Faculty.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor going to visit?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected are estimated to be a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowness are common, however, pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Depending on pathogens, the hepatitis viruses are spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. by contaminated foods or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transferred through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, scratch or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to vaccine against the viruses A and B, anyway, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A show about two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and breach.
Then the yellowness occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last for up to two-three weeks.
About 1 million people worldwide die annually from those caused by hepatitis B, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every ten people infected in medications treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected don’t even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells – in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check tests, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C diseased worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already demonstrable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the doctor with the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is recognized to be healed, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
The 30th of September is the World Day of Hepatitis, held for the first time in 2004 by patient conferences worldwide.
The goal of the action is to strengthen the awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its emergence and the importance of early recognition.
